John,

Yes, suites are run in the order that tests are added.  As you say, 
depending on this feature for test correctness can make tests difficult 
to manage.  However, I often fiddle with test ordering to make fast 
tests or tests likely to fail run first.

    David Saff

John H. E. wrote:

&gt; Hi all,
&gt;
&gt; I know that I shouldn&#39;t write tests that depend on other tests etc.,
&gt; but I would still like to know for sure...
&gt;
&gt; When I run a JUnit test suite (&quot;regular&quot;, not Active), are the tests
&gt; run in the order in which they were added to the suite?
&gt;
&gt; E.g., if my test suite is created as follows:
&gt;
&gt; public static Test suite(){
&gt;
&gt;    TestSuite suite =  new TestSuite();
&gt;    suite.addTest(new TestCaseTest(&quot;testNumberOne&quot;));
&gt;    suite.addTest(new TestCaseTest(&quot;testNumberTwo&quot;));
&gt;    suite.addTest(new TestCaseTest(&quot;testA&quot;));
&gt;    return suite;
&gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Can I be sure that when I run the test suite (e.g. using the
&gt; junit.textui.TestRunner), the test are executed in the following
&gt; order?
&gt;
&gt;    testNumberOne
&gt;    testNumberTwo
&gt;    testA
&gt;
&gt; My testing indicates this, but I obviously can not know this for sure
&gt; from simple testing.
